    "summary": "Professional historian specialised in the history of Dutch (military) aviation and Dutch orders and decorations. Direct experience with education. For more then a decade he was a visiting lecturer at the Royal Military Academy and the Netherlands Defence College. He is the author of the following books: 500 jaar Marine (co-authors L.L.M. Eekhout and A.Th. I . Hazenoot  (Amsterdam 1988), Ab Origine Flexibilis. Luchtmacht Stafschool 1949-1991 (Den Haag 1991), Ab Origine Flexibilis 1949-1992, supplement (Den Haag 1993), 322 Squadron. Sporen van zijn verleden, lijnen in zijn geschiedenis (Den Haag 1993), Check the Horizon. De Koninklijke Luchtmacht en het conflict in voormalig Joegoslavi\u00eb 1991-1995 (Den Haag 2001, co-author Rolf de Winter), Van Hofstad naar Baronie. De luchtmacht in Den Haag en Breda (Den Haag 2007, co-author Rolf de Winter) and Luchtmachtreservisten Toen & Nu, Groep Luchtmacht Reserve 2004-2014 (Breda 2014, co-author C.J. Spek) \nLot of experience in editing books and articles. He was the editor-in-chief of Twice a Citizen, the magazine/the digital newsletter for the reservists of the Royal Netherlands Air Force. \nOrganised almost 80 battlefield-tours to the WW 1 battlefields around Ypres (Belgium). \nIn 2009 he designed the badge of the (former) 600 Squadron of the RNLAF Reserve. He was also the deviser of the name \"Cockpit\" for the building next to the Air Force Tower in Breda, The Netherlands.\nFurthermore he was for 10 years a visiting lecturer (History Royal Netherlands Air Force) to the KMA, KMSL and IDL.\nFor many years he is a pioneer in relation to the participation of the RNLAF Reserve in the yearly commemoration on May 10th of the Battle of The Hague in May 1940 on the former Ypenburg Airbase.\nThe last few years he wrote articles on the relation between the RNLAF and the city of The Hague and surroundings in the periodical \"Haagse Tijden\", the historical newspaper for a 50 years plus audience. In the last quarter of 2020 he was coach/mentor of a collegue officer who followed the MDV to become a major.\nSeveral times in the last few years he succesfully attempted to acquire lost or never issued decorations for the next of kin of Dutch veterans.\nUntil now he acquired 1 Oorlogsherdenkingskruis with clasp May 1940, 4 x Mobilisatie Oorlogskruizen, 3 x Ereteken voor Oorlog en Vrede, 2x Demobilisatie Insigne KNIL, 1x Herinneringsinsigne KNIL, 1x Canadian Volunteer Service Medal, etc\n\n\nSpecialities: Historical research, editing books and articles, organising battlefield-tours, education, orders and decorations, ceremonies and protocol",
